      "content": "You are absolutely right that nationalism can foster social cohesion and motivate citizens to protect their communities, as seen during wartime or during national rebuilding efforts. However, in sociology, the danger lies not in the existence of national identity itself, but in the rigid, exclusionary definition of who belongs to that nation. If that shared identity becomes a tool to dehumanize outsiders or justify state violence, the \"common good\" transforms into a tyranny of the majority, which ultimately undermines the very stability it seeks to protect.",
